Ambiguous (adjective)
Open to more than one interpretation; unclear.
"The instructions were ambiguous, causing confusion among students."

2. Coherent (adjective)
Logical and consistent; easy to understand.
"She presented a coherent argument in her essay."

3. Compensate (verb)
To make up for something; to balance out.
"Extra practice helped compensate for his lack of experience."

4. Deduce (verb)
To reach a conclusion through reasoning and evidence.
"From the clues, the scientist was able to deduce the cause of the reaction."

5. Elaborate (verb/adjective)
To explain in more detail; or, very detailed and complex.
"The teacher asked her to elaborate on her answer."

6. Evident (adjective)
Clearly seen or understood; obvious.
"It was evident from the data that the experiment had succeeded."

7. Fluctuate (verb)
To rise and fall irregularly; to change frequently.
"Temperatures fluctuate greatly in desert regions."

8. Implication (noun)
A conclusion that can be drawn from something, even if not directly stated.
"The implications of the research are still being studied."

9. Predominant (adjective)
Present as the strongest or main element; most common.
"Agriculture was the predominant industry in the region."

10. Validate (verb)
To confirm or prove the truth or accuracy of something.
"Further studies are needed to validate these findings."

